We got to play Pathfinder 2 on Saturday, which we had not done for a while. My family had been thinking we might go to the Renaissance Festival that day, but between me not feeling good and the weather getting a lot cooler, we decided to skip it this year.

We were still in the Abomination Vault and we found a section we hadn't gone through before. There was a guard spider and we took care of it pretty easily, but the Drow behind Door #1 were pretty upset with us. My character ended up getting drained and enfeebled, which was very inconvenient. And it was due to a disease, so it was not going away with time. Luckily our cleric and our ranger managed to mostly patch me up, but I was still struggling for a lot of the evening.

So that was a fight, and then almost immediately after that, we found another Drow guard who got away from us.

Instead of trying to chase her down on our little Dwarf legs or set up an ambush for the group that was almost certainly coming our way, we went down another hallway, where we found ANOTHER room full of Drow.

While we were getting our rear ends handed to us there, the other guard came back with all of her friends and we were fighting on two fronts.

It was tough for a while, but the module had given these Drow longbows, which were not great in the size or rooms we were in (that helped). And our Ranger had previously looted some exploding arrows he had not gotten to use, and this fight was kind of perfect for those. That was fun.

Eventually, we got through it all, but my shield is useless until I can repair it and my character is WAY down on hit points. That's where we stopped, so I am hoping we can take some time to rest up before we trigger the next encounter.

#Pathfinder2

An interesting one is that complimentary medicine is basically focussed around two outcomes - how do we make men permanently erect and continuously horny, and how do we make women able to have babies. So lots of the supplement research and production is trials to try and see if any given thing does that. Interestingly, and usefully, when these trials about "does this herb give men an iron dick and insatiable sexual appetite" get the outcome "no not really." they occasionally accidentally find other things that are actually useful.

I think ‚Äúfedi meta‚Äù is a misnomer. What is being discussed and decided is policy. If you decide policy, that makes you a politician.

Fedi meta is politics. Instance admins and their peers are politicians.

Big instances means big power, which means big politics and big politicians.

Here's a truism I found very useful when I did politics. Three kinds of people are drawn to politics: Those who really want to make the world better for others, those who are really in it for themselves, and those who significantly belong to both groups.

People who belong to none of those two groups are not very attracted to politics, so they don't show up. Power attracts only those who want to either use it or wear it or both.

And this is important: A lot of the time it is both. Being in it for others and for yourself makes you more motivated and more likely to come out on top.

Fedi meta is politics.
Those who decide policy are politicians.
All politicians are sus.
